for the first time in paperback, he argues that strict constraints are inconsistent with the freedom enjoyed by musicians of the period.The author takes an entirely new look at ornamentation, and particularly that of J. S. Bach. He draws on extensive research in England, France, Germany, Italy, and the United States to show that prevailing interpretations are based on inadequate evidence. These restrictive interpretations have been far-reaching in their effect on style. By questioning them, this work continues to stimulate a reorientation in our understandiing of Baroque and post-Baroque music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aAldrich, Putnam.  aBernhard, Christoph.  aDadelsen, Georg von.  aDellain, trill.  aDoppelaccent: Marpurg.  aFerguson, Howard.  aFranceschini, Petronio.  aGedoppelter Accent: Walther.  aJacobi, Erwin R.  aKast, Paul.  aLang, Paul Henry.  aLegrenzi, Giovanni.  aMann, Alfred.  aNardini, Pietro.  aNorth, Roger.  aPenna, Lorenzo, arpg.  aRabey, Wladimir.  aRaparlier, vibrato.  aSchering, Arnold.  aSeiffert, Max.  aSignoretti.  aSymbols, early F.  aTartini, Giuseppe.  aWolf, Ernst Wilhelm.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691213347zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691213347423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691213347.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aP